The deductio ad impossibile, as it is usually rendered, (abductio would perhaps be better) is one species of the συλλογισμὸς ἐξ ὑποθέσεως, (see Appendix, note L) the object of which is, to prove the truth of a given problem, by inferring a salsehood from the assumption of its contradictory. This may be employed in the reduction of syllogisms, but it is also used for other purposeS, as by Geometers, (Euclid. i. 7.)
